{"timestamp": "2025-12-02 17:23:09.567587", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Codes: K - kernel route, C - connected, S - static, R - RIP,\\n       O - OSPF, I - IS-IS, B - BGP, E - EIGRP, N - NHRP,\\n       T - Table, v - VNC, V - VNC-Direct, A - Babel, F - PBR,\\n       f - OpenFabric,\\n       > - selected route, * - FIB route, q - queued, r - rejected, b - backup\\n       t - trapped, o - offload failure\\n\\nO>* 10.1.1.0/24 [110/40] via 172.16.0.14, eth7, weight 1, 00:02:30\\nO>* 10.1.2.0/24 [110/40] via 172.16.0.14, eth7, weight 1, 00:02:30\\nO>* 10.2.1.0/24 [110/40] via 172.16.0.14, eth7, weight 1, 00:02:30\\nO>* 10.2.2.0/24 [110/40] via 172.16.0.14, eth7, weight 1, 00:02:30\\nO   10.200.0.0/24 [110/10] is directly connected, br0, weight 1, 00:03:20\\nC>* 10.200.0.0/24 is directly connected, br0, 00:03:21\\nO>* 172.16.0.0/31 [110/30] via 172.16.0.14, eth7, weight 1, 00:02:35\\nO>* 172.16.0.2/31 [110/20] via 172.16.0.14, eth7, weight 1, 00:02:35\\nO>* 172.16.0.4/31 [110/20] via 172.16.0.14, eth7, weight 1, 00:02:35\\nO>* 172.16.0.6/31 [110/30] via 172.16.0.14, eth7, weight 1, 00:02:35\\nO>* 172.16.0.8/31 [110/30] via 172.16.0.14, eth7, weight 1, 00:02:35\\nO>* 172.16.0.10/31 [110/30] via 172.16.0.14, eth7, weight 1, 00:02:30\\nO>* 172.16.0.12/31 [110/30] via 172.16.0.14, eth7, weight 1, 00:02:30\\nO   172.16.0.14/31 [110/10] is directly connected, eth7, weight 1, 00:03:20\\nC>* 172.16.0.14/31 is directly connected, eth7, 00:03:21' name='frr_show_ip_route' id='28421026-a127-4376-b5dc-7f67e35fd798' tool_call_id='call_q53rxOBsNXtdyWSnuxjyrZ68'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5-mini", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
{"timestamp": "2025-12-02 17:23:55.762132", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report — Enterprise OSPF Network\nSummary\n- Overall network reachability for user hosts is good: hosts in 10.<core>.<dist>.0/24 can reach DNS (10.200.0.2), DHCP (10.200.0.8), the public web servers (10.200.0.3–6) and the published load balancer (10.200.0.7). No packet loss was observed for these paths in the sampled test.\n- The load balancer (10.200.0.7) can reach all backend web servers (20.200.0.2–4). However, the backend web servers in 20.200.0.0/24 are not reachable from user hosts or visible in the server_access_router routing table (they are only reachable from the load balancer / internal backend network).\n- The routing table on server_access_router shows OSPF routes to the user subnets (10.1.x/10.2.x) and a directly connected 10.200.0.0/24, but contains no route for 20.200.0.0/24.\n\nKey evidence\n1) Reachability scan highlights:\n- Hosts -> load_balancer and -> web_server_0..3 : status \"ok\" (0% loss).\n- Hosts -> backend_web_0..2 (20.200.0.2–4): status \"unknown\" (no successful reachability recorded from hosts).\n- load_balancer -> backend_web_0..2: status \"ok\" (the load balancer has connectivity to backends).\n2) server_access_router routing table (excerpt):\n- 10.200.0.0/24 is directly connected (br0).\n- OSPF routes to 10.1.x and 10.2.x are present via 172.16.0.14 on eth7.\n- No route entry for 20.200.0.0/24 is present.\n\nObserved abnormal behaviors / deviations from expected state\n- The backend web servers’ addresses (20.200.0.2–20.200.0.4) are not visible in the wider routed topology (server_access_router lacks routes to 20.200.0.0/24) and therefore are not reachable from user hosts. This is a clear divergence from the generic statement that “infrastructure and server networks are advertised by FRR OSPF” — the 20.200.0.0/24 network is not being advertised/learned.\n- Some individual latency/jitter anomalies exist in the ping statistics (large rtt_mdev and occasional high max RTTs for a few host-to-server pairs), e.g., a few entries with high rtt_avg and large mdev values. These did not correspond with packet loss in the sampled test, so they appear to be transient performance variations rather than hard failures.\n\nLocalization — devices and interfaces implicated\n- load_balancer: Local connectivity to backend web servers is confirmed (pings from load_balancer to 20.200.0.x succeed). The LB is the only device sampled that has direct reachability into 20.200.0.0/24.\n- backend_web_0..2: Physically/responding on 20.200.0.0/24; reachable from load_balancer and between backends in some cases, but not from hosts or server_access_router.\n- server_access_router: Does not have a route for 20.200.0.0/24 (routing table shows 10.200.0.0/24 only). This router is the aggregation point for the server farm and is the place where an absent OSPF advertisement or static route would show up; it therefore localizes the lack of reachability/advertisement to the server-side routing domain.\n\nLikely root cause(s)\n- Intentional isolation or missing routing advertisement:\n  - The behavior is consistent with the 20.200.0.0/24 network being intentionally isolated (only attached to the LB and internal backend interfaces) and not being redistributed/advertised into OSPF. If the design intent is to prevent direct host access to backends, this silence from OSPF is consistent (and expected).\n  - Alternatively, if the design intends OSPF to advertise all server networks (as the description ambiguously states), then the root cause is a configuration omission: the 20.200.0.0/24 network is not being advertised into OSPF on the server-side router(s) (or on the load_balancer if it is expected to advertise it). That omission prevents server_access_router and thus the rest of the network from learning a route to the backend network.\n- No evidence of link or device failure for the public-facing items:\n  - DNS, DHCP, load balancer and public web servers (10.200.0.x) are reachable and responding; OSPF adjacency and forwarding for those networks are functioning.\n- The transient RTT outliers are likely caused by momentary congestion, CPU scheduling or test-timing variation on individual hosts, not by systemic forwarding failures (no packet loss observed).\n\nImplications and relevant findings\n- If the network intent is to restrict direct host-to-backend access and force all host access via load balancer (web99), the current state matches that intent: hosts cannot reach backend IPs directly and must use the LB which can reach backends.\n- If the network intent is to advertise backend networks via OSPF for some reason (for example, for monitoring, management, or cross-data-center reachability), then the lack of OSPF advertisement for 20.200.0.0/24 is a misconfiguration and explains the “unknown” reachability results from hosts.\n- The server_access_router routing table confirms the absence of 20.200.0.0/24 in the global routing plane.\n\nAdditional notes\n- Load balancer health: LB can reach all backends and can reach DNS/DHCP — LB is functioning correctly in its role.\n- Backend-to-backend connectivity: backends show internal connectivity among themselves (some inter-backend pings succeeded), but many servers outside that domain show “unknown” reachability to 20.200 addresses — consistent with isolation.\n- The OSPF routes to the user subnets on server_access_router are present and appear stable.\n\nConclusion\n- Network is largely healthy for host access to published services (DNS, DHCP, frontend web, LB). No packet loss was observed on those paths.\n- The primary abnormality is the absence of the 20.200.0.0/24 (backend web) network from the global routing plane (server_access_router routing table) and from hosts’ reachability tests. This results in user hosts not being able to reach backend web servers directly.\n- Root cause: the backend network (20.200.0.0/24) is not being advertised/learned via OSPF beyond the LB/backend segment — either by design (intentional isolation) or due to a configuration omission (missing OSPF advertisement). The relevant devices to inspect further (if required) are the load_balancer (its interface to the backend network and any routing/advertising settings) and the server-side FRR configuration (to confirm whether 20.200.0.0/24 should be advertised and, if so, why it is currently absent).\n\nIf you want, I can next:\n- Pull FRR OSPF/BGP/advertisement configuration from server_access_router and from the load_balancer host, or\n- Show the routing table from a core router to confirm whether 20.200.0.0/24 is known anywhere else in the network. (No changes or mitigations will be made unless you request them.)", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 34258, "output_tokens": 3599, "total_tokens": 37857, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 33408}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 1984}}}
